Vatinius by Calvus, mentioned in c. 53, may well have taken place in 56 rae, instead of in the fall of 54. Furthermore, c. rr, which was surely written toward the close of 55 ne, shows a decided change in the feeling of Catullus toward Caesar, and accords well with the statement of Suetonius (lul. 73), that after Catullus had angered Caesar by his epigrams concerning him and Mamurra, a reconciliation with the poet took place, apparently at his father’s house at Verona. It is hardly credible that if Catullus lived during the exciting years that followed 55 ne, the only indication of his new feeling toward Caesar should be the reference in c. 11, and that this was followed by silence. Such neutrality was not the fashion among the young friends whom Caesar was constantly winning to himself from the ranks of his political opponents. There seems, indeed, to be an indication in c. rr that Catullus might be expecting some post under the great commander. But the most satisfactory conclusion is that death came within a short time after the close ol 55 rac, and anticipated all hopedfor activities (cf, however, 5 5ο).
